feelings about work-family balance, and we find, unexpectedly,
that women and men report similar levels of success and kinds of
work-family tradeoffs. We find some gender differences, however.
For men, imbalance is predicted by longer work hours, wives who
work fewer hours, perceived unfairness in sharing housework,
marital unhappiness, and tradeoffs made at work for family and at
home for work. For women, only marital unhappiness and sacrifices
at home are imbalancing, and for women who are employed
full-time, young children are.},
